[[File:Lacerba Magazine 1913.jpg|thumb|The first Issue, in Florence, 1 January 1913]] '''''Lacerba''''' was an Italian literary journal. It was started as a fortnightly magazine on 1 January 1913<ref name="Brooker">{{cite book|author1=Peter Brooker|author2=Sascha Bru|author3=Andrew Thacker|author4=Christian Weikop|title=The Oxford Critical and Cultural History of Modernist Magazines: Europe 1880 - 1940|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bvsfioiQ8k8C&pg=PA471|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-965958-6|page=471}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/327151/Lacerba|title=Lacerba|work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]}}</ref> which was closely associated with the [[Futurism|Futurist]] movement.<ref name=alan5/> Its frequency was later changed to weekly.<ref name=alan5/> The paper was based in [[Florence]].<ref name="alan5">{{cite book|author=Alan Bartram|title=Futurist Typography and the Liberated Text|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRC5KvV7EgEC&pg=PA117|accessdate=18 June 2015|year=2005|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-11432-X|page=117}}</ref>
The paper had no official editor. [[Ardengo Soffici]] and [[Giovanni Papini]] were two of the principal contributors.<ref name=alan5/> ''Lacerba'' ceased publication on 22 May 1915.<ref name=alan5/>
