{{Infobox Artwork | image_file = Paul Cézanne 185.jpg | title = The Basket of Apples | artist = [[Paul Cézanne]] | year = 1895 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 65 | width_metric = 80 | height_imperial = 25.6 | width_imperial = 31.5 | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = [[Chicago]] | museum = [[Art Institute of Chicago]] }}
'''''The Basket of Apples''''' is a [[still life]] oil painting by French artist [[Paul Cézanne]]. It belongs to the [[Helen Birch Bartlett Memorial Collection]] of the [[Art Institute of Chicago]].
The piece is often noted for its disjointed [[perspective (graphical)|perspective]]. It has been described as a balanced composition due to its unbalanced parts;<ref name=Schapiro>Schapiro, Meyer (1988). ''Cézanne'', New York: Harry N. Abrams, Inc, p.96. {{ISBN|0-8109-1043-8}}.</ref> the tilted bottle, the incline of the basket, and the foreshortened lines of the cookies mesh with the lines of the tablecloth.<ref name=Schapiro/> Additionally, the right side of the tabletop is not in the same plane as the left side, as if the image simultaneously reflects two viewpoints.<ref name=AIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/artaccess/AA_Impressionist/pages/IMP_10.shtml |title=Paul Cézanne: The Basket of Apples |publisher=The Art Institute of Chicago: Art Access |date=August 2004 |accessdate=2011-04-27}}</ref> Paintings such as this helped form a bridge between [[Impressionism]] and [[Cubism]].<ref name=AIC/>
